Performance Sports Groups Headwinds And Their Continued Growth - Performance Sports Group Ltd. (NYSE:PSG) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Performance Sports Groups Headwinds And Their Continued GrowthNov.12.14 | About: Performance Sports (PSG) Michael Ambrozewicz Long/short equity, Growth, research analyst, long-term horizonSummaryIncreasing intense competition from other competitors in the sporting goods industry.The lack of a youthful sales force as a foundation for future growth.Concerns in administration and improving their balance sheet.Performance Sports Group Ltd. (PSG), formerly Bauer Performance Sports, is a publicly traded stock in the New York Stock Exchange. It is a leading international hockey supplier and has recently incorporated lacrosse, baseball and uniforms to expand its supply chain. It's a company that is deeply rooted in Canadian psychic and eager to expand their investor base into the United States. However, it's one of the few companies that I can say with certainty that will remain neutral in the $17.00 to $21.00 range.
There's a very disturbing trend that Bauer Hockey, a branch under Performance Sports Group, incorporated with respect to how retailers market their products. Retailers in Canada, USA, and Europe are required to retail Bauer products at the suggested retail price, regardless of how dominant the retailer is in the market. Their conventional wisdom, and by that I mean sales managers that were brought into the organization from the old Cooper days, have indicated that the purchasing consumer relies on a 35 mile radius to purchase hockey equipment. Competitors such as Reebok/CCM, Warrior, Easton, have suggested to retailers for their elite level products that a "call for pricing" is in effect. In fact, the Reebok/CCM sales manager said that in times of slow business where you must move product, the "call for pricing" allows retailers to move stock quicker and get a return on investment. Reebok/CCM had their biggest and most successful launch with reviving the Tacks brand. In fact, retailers can't keep up with the demand.
Performance Sports Group exacerbated their problem by not allowing retailers to move product in a timely fashion and to repeat with them. With Bauer products, retailers will book and not repeat. Even if Bauer has a new product launch, retailers will have a reservation to book more than their required minimum. In the long run, they will maintain revenue but never exceed expectations. How do I know this? I worked part-time in a hockey store for five years supporting my education. Bauer hockey developed a certain moat by dominating the hockey market. However, this "moat" they developed is plagued with a tinge of arrogance, which is counterproductive to revenue growth. They have the best and the most innovative products in the world, but this is not reflected by their sales force. Many times the Bauer representative would come into the store, tell a couple of jokes, and leave without an order. The Reebok/CCM, Warrior, and Easton representatives represent a younger and more driven generation. Any time my former boss gave me an open to buy budget, the younger Reebok/CCM, Warrior, and Easton reps were much more eager to rake in revenue and promote their brand.

Apple's (AAPL) success story is based on innovative products. Their sales force from top to bottom is based on youth which has become a key foundation in their growth story. Performance Sports Group lacks a young and energetic sales force that can religiously convey why retailers should deploy 70% of their shelf space to Bauer products. When I met the new Reebok/CCM representative, the first words that came out of his mouth were, "I want 60% of your shelf space, what will it take?"
Increased revenue is based on the allocation of shelf space. A company's moat relies on its ability to understand its competition, the marketplace, and the role the company plays to increase their revenue in the environment. What they need to do is target other companies so that they do not gain a competitive advantage over them. Through acquisition, Performance Sports Group was able to generate revenue year-round, a positive sign for investors. But in order for Performance Sports Group to think globally and execute their goals, they need to emphasize the fact that by having innovative products they need the most innovative sales force. This comes with youth instead of an old boys' club living in the past. Investors invest in youth, motivated management, and innovation. The reason why is because it provides them with confidence that a revenue stream is likely to continue.
Hockey is one of the few sports that demand an enormous amount of commitment from parents. Costs involving hockey registration are up 30% since 1999. Gas prices also continue to rise, making travel to and from hockey more expensive. Hockey equipment is not supplied by most organizations anymore. Escalating real estate prices have made building arenas infeasible and non-profitable from an economic standpoint. If arenas in Canada and the USA are not being built then the revenue from hockey will slowly begin to deteriorate. Even the 5% growth that the US has experienced in hockey registration over the past year pales in comparison in the amount of kids who have not played hockey since the 2008-2009 recession. It is one of the few sports heavily impacted by slowdowns in economic business cycles. If there are expectations of interest rates rising in the US and Canada, then hockey parents will be the first to consider alternative sports to replace hockey. House league registration is down across Canada in both urban and rural areas. The shift in demographics across North America has resulted in a smaller proportion of kids as the population continues to age. Men's recreational hockey leagues have also suffered as the awareness for injuries such as concussions have been shown to be more dangerous than previously thought. The recreational leagues cater from men 25-45 years of age which have a high disposable income for the purchase of hockey equipment. In general, hockey suppliers are ignoring this huge market as the potential for growth continues to dwindle.

What Performance Sports Group did successfully through acquisition was increasing their market share in hockey, lacrosse, and perhaps more importantly, baseball. The hockey equipment market is less fragmented than that of baseball. You have two dominant suppliers and maybe one or two fringe suppliers that retailers rely upon in the business of hockey equipment. In a stagnant hockey market, that is good for Bauer. The only growth is by taking away market shares from competitors such as Reebok/CCM. The baseball market is crowded with large suppliers such as Rawlings, Wilson, Mizuno, etc. who dominate in certain categories that help distinguish themselves from others. However, through the recent acquisition of Easton, Bauer has taken over as the dominant supplier of baseball bats. In lacrosse, Bauer dominates the business of head protection through their line of Cascade helmets. However, Warrior, Brine and STX still come out on top in terms of supplying teams with protective gear. At over $300 million per year, the team business stands out as a lucrative growth for businesses looking for additional revenue.
It's interesting to note that Performance Sports Group took a different approach with their business model. They hired sales representatives to go directly to teams and allocate their business to a limited amount of retailers. Retailers who don't get the business push the competitor's products instead. By going directly to teams, Bauer is unable to charge more for team-wear and team uniforms. The team-wear business is one of the few businesses that carry depreciating margins because teams expect low prices every year. Additionally, if Bauer is late to deliver their product, they continually have to make amends in order to receive business for the following year, thus reducing margins even further. Other competitors that traditionally use retailers as an intermediary have also gone directly to teams to compete with Bauer. Since Bauer went directly to teams for direct business, who's responsible if the team decides to not pay the bill? The retailer should not be liable for unpaid team business as a result of Bauer choosing to handle all the work directly. Even though CCM has an NHL licensing agreement I can see them further strengthening their jersey line by purchasing companies like Athletic Knit that directly competes with Inaria. Athletic Knit is a global leader in the jersey business and produced in Canada. With Athletic Knit, many hockey associations know that their deliveries are always on time, and they can take that to the bank.

Kohlberg Management VI, LLC recently completed an additional sell-down in its position in Performance Sports Group of approximately 2 million common shares, resulting in aggregate proceeds for Kohlberg of CAD $37,550,000. The sell-down of the position leaves Kohlberg with 5.3% of Performance Sports Group's issued and outstanding common shares on a non-diluted basis which still maintains their position of being one of the largest shareholders of the company.
Performance Sports Group's first quarter results turned out to be fairly successful. The company reported a strong 28% in total revenue vs. a year ago, an 8% increase in hockey revenue and 7% increase in lacrosse revenue. Adjusted Gross Profit increased 19% to $73.4 million and adjusted EBITDA grew 8% to $39.9 million. An increase in assets coupled with a decrease in liabilities and an increase in equity signals a very positive outlook on the future of the company, especially from a shareholder's point of view. However, even though gross profits increased, the large expenditure in selling, general and administrative expenses resulted in a lower value of net and comprehensive income. Basic earnings per common share decreased from $0.61 to $0.27 and diluted earnings per common share from $0.57 to $0.26. Even though more shares were issued, the loss suffered in earnings per common share shouldn't have been as drastic as they turned out to be, which can be partially blamed on the large increase in selling, general, and administrative expenses. Other NYSE-listed sporting good companies including Under Armour (UA) and Nike Inc. (NKE) generally follow a percentage-of-sales or net income approach when dealing with their expenses. For example, from 2013 to 2014 Under Armour experienced an approximate increase in gross profit of 29.2% and an approximate 26% increase in net income. Accordingly, Under Armour's SG&A expenses experienced reasonable growth of an approximate 29.9%. On the other hand, Performance Sports Group's increase in SG&A expenses of approximately 38% is quite large in comparison to its 7% increase in gross profit and -46% decrease in net income. When examining similar companies in the same industry as Performance Sports Group, such a large increase in SG&A can signal a problem for the common investor who may question how efficiently management is spending the company's money and whether valuable cash flow is being wasted.

What is encouraging is that the company's long-term debt levels decreased while their short-term debt levels increased. What is discouraging is that none of the upper management owns any shares. RBC has a price target of $20, Wunderlich's price target is $24, and Imperial Capital's price target is $21. It has a 50-day average of $16.78. I feel that this stock is fairly valued and the average price of approximately $20.64 should hold. With future headwinds of the higher US dollar, rising costs of raw materials, and a declining hockey market may prove to be more challenging for Performance Sports Group. The acquisitions they made were good and investors can be assured of year-round revenue. Their sales force needs improvement, and until then, I have a long-term hold on it of $20.
Even though Adidas AG (OTCQX:ADDDF) is divesting their interest in Reebok, Adidas will make a bid for the National Hockey League's jerseys in 2016. They have more capital and resources available, giving them a substantial advantage over Performance Sports Group in the execution of such a potential deal. Adidas has two choices with CCM, either they sell it or come to terms with the fact that hockey has become a duopoly. The advantage of a duopoly is less fragmentation due to only two competitors in the marketplace. The question is whether or not Adidas is serious in increasing capital expenditure towards CCM to gain on Performance Sports Group's market share. This will demonstrate that the Adidas CEO is confident in translating the increase in hockey market share towards overall market share in the sporting goods industry.
A duopoly should not be undermined, it should be viewed as an opportunity to increase revenue. CCM and Reebok dominate the goalie market in the National Hockey League even though Bauer has indicated that they are the leaders of this position. We need to clarify that Bauer has 54% of the head protection market for goaltenders. However, in terms of protective goal equipment, Reebok and CCM own about 50% of the overall market share. Bauer comes at a distant third in protective goal equipment. 65% of boutique hockey store revenues are generated through the sale of composite sticks, individually ranging from $59.99 to $299.99. Many retailers wait for closeout lists to purchase these sticks. Manufacturers such as Warrior, Easton, CCM, etc. come out with closeout lists, taking away available dollars to purchase Bauer equipment. CCM composite sticks in the high $200 range are less expensive for retailers than Bauer sticks in the same price range. Closeouts play a significant role increasing margins of hockey retailers. Suppliers such as Easton, CCM, and Warrior offer closeout lists for every retailer in the market. On the other hand, Performance Sports Group fails to recognize the importance of closeout lists as they only offer them to a select few. Again, it's based on patronage from an old boy's club instead of valuing revenue as revenue. Competitors' closeouts are not going to return to normal levels anytime soon. In fact, retailers have indicated that closeouts are coming out earlier than previous years. Furthermore, it takes away open-to-buy and creates an anticipatory reaction from retailers to purchase products at a lower price. For Bauer, competitors' closeouts provide very little visibility for product repeat demand and may not translate into realized sales or future growth. What's alarming is that closeouts reinforce the core business of hockey, a sport that is shrinking and deteriorating at a quicker pace than many have anticipated. According to the Sports and Fitness Industry, global hockey participation and registration has grown at a measly 1% annually over the last eight years.

What Performance Sports Group does effectively is spreadsheet coaching. The focus is on sales staff hitting numbers. The innovation that is taking place in hockey equipment should translate in exceeding expectations rather than meeting a quota. What Performance Sports Group lacks is a follow-through in sales which ultimately leads to fizzling sales momentum. As an investor, I want Performance Sports Group to exceed their expectations. Brand-name exposure in the National Hockey League and social media are good tools for creating demand knowledge and perhaps the experience for the product. However, a strong and innovative sales force is able to articulate to retailers that their money is well spent. In the long run, this translates into rewards for investors.
Disclosure: The author has no positions in any stocks mentioned, and no plans to initiate any positions within the next 72 hours. 
